helpdesk-note.body-html: Tickets with ids 5588 and 5578 are merged into this ticket.

helpdesk-note.body:
Upon login you get an error pop up in the bottom right that says
Windows could not connect to the Group Policy Client service. This problem prevents standard users from logging on to the system. As an administrative user, you can review the System Event Log for details about why the service didn't respond.
I was unable to see anything significant in the event log. I readded it to the domain and tried to reinstall Windows Updates, however, the windows updates will not install the one remaining update. It will start to download the update (which is 9mb) sticks at 0 for about 2-3 minutes, and then fails. Need to do more research
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Upon login you get an error pop up in the bottom right that says

Windows could not connect to the Group Policy Client service. This problem prevents standard users from logging on to the system. As an administrative user, you can review the System Event Log for details about why the service didn't respond.

It will start to download the update (which is 9mb) sticks at 0 for about 2-3 minutes, and then fails. Need to do more research

helpdesk-note.body: If unresponsive, power cycle the printer. Make sure you are using the main power switch to do so and not just the switch on top of the printer. helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello,
I am writing because the next group of undergraduate international students will be arriving on Monday, February 29th for their orientation week. We are hoping to have them pick up their laptops and have someone show them how to log in and use their mymsoe, blackboard and outlook accounts on Wednesday, March 2nd sometime in the afternoon. It would also be great if they could be shown how to use Follow You printing.
We are estimating to have between 10-15 students start for the Spring quarter. Please let me know if this would be a possibility for this quarter. Ideally we would like to have this type of IT orientation for each group of new international students, both at the ESL and undergraduate level.

helpdesk-note.body: Good Morning Kayla. Yes indeed we can have an orientation and laptop handout on March 2nd. I am prepared for all the students you have. I will provide laptop and power brick for each student. We will need access to ethernet cables for each student to perform their first logon. Once we have logged onto and shut down each laptop with the ethernet cable plugged in, all other work can be done over wireless. I propose using the CC Great Room as we have access to ethernet there. If you have another spot that you would like to use, I am open to that as long as we have ethernet access. I can also provide for this event the actual ethernet cables to use. Peter Pfister
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Good Morning Kayla.

Yes indeed we can have an orientation and laptop handout on March 2nd.  I am prepared for all the students you have.  I will provide laptop and power brick for each student.  We will need access to ethernet cables for each student to perform their first logon.  Once we have logged onto and shut down each laptop with the ethernet cable plugged in, all other work can be done over wireless.  I propose using the CC Great Room as we have access to ethernet there.  If you have another spot that you would like to use, I am open to that as long as we have ethernet access.  I can also provide for this event the actual ethernet cables to use.

Peter Pfister

helpdesk-note.body:
Pam,
Thanks for bringing this to our attention. However, MSOE has decided that moving forward, we will be using cloud solutions in place of local solutions whenever it's prudent. Locally stored data is expensive to buy and to maintain, and due to redundancy, 1 GB of data can require as much as 3 GB of space to store. Use of the O: and M: drives became such that it was no longer cost effective to continue adding physical hardware to maintain the ever-growing need for space. In 2014, MSOE decided to partner with Box.com to offer each student, staff, and faculty 20 GB of storage space in the cloud. Our hope is that eventually we can retire our local storage entirely. However, for the time being, while we wont be abandoning the O: and M: drives, we won't be adding additional storage.
If you have any questions regarding how to best use Box.com, please let us know, and we can have someone show you the ropes.
Thanks,

helpdesk-note.body:
Pam,
Box is designed for enterprise use. It allows several levels of sharing, including read only, edit, and ownership. You can share via a link, or through MSOE email addresses to provide controlled access. Some file types allow collaboration and multiple simultaneous user edits. It almost every feature, Box provides a better experience to file use.
For this Donations Database file, I'd suggest you upload it to Box, decide who will be the owner or owners of the file and set them up when sending out initial Share invites, and set the rest of the users up as editors only. If you need assistance, the Helpdesk can walk you through the specifics. I think (I hope!) you'll find that it's a better experience than using the O: drive.
Thanks Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4869

Dear Helpdesk Staff,
Could you please change the permission of the group EEX-Students@msoe.edu<mailto:EEX-Students@msoe.edu> such that I can deliver email to this group. Thank you.
Rich Kelnhofer
Richard W. Kelnhofer, Ph.D. Program Director – Electrical Engineering Milwaukee School of Engineering 414-277-2306
_____________________________________________ From: Microsoft Outlook Sent: Wednesday, February 10, 2016 12:56 PM To: Kelnhofer, Dr. Richard Subject: Undeliverable: CS 498-001
http://products.office.com/en-us/CMSImages/Office365Logo_Orange.png?version=b8d100a9-0a8b-8e6a-88e1-ef488fee0470 Your message to the group EEX-Students@msoe.edu couldn't be delivered.
The group EEX-Students only accepts messages from people on its allowed senders list, and your email address isn't on the list.
kelnhofer Office 365 EEX-Students Sender Action Required
Sender not allowed
How to Fix It Ask the owner of the group to grant you permission to send to the group, and then try to send a message again. If the group belongs to a different organization than yours, contact the organization's customer service department for assistance. If the group is in your organization and you don't know who the group owner is, you can find it by doing the following in either Outlook on the web or Outlook:
• Open your Sent folder, and then select the original message. • If you're using Outlook on the web, select the group name located on the To or CC line. If you're using Outlook, double-click the group name on the To or CC line. • In Outlook on the web, from the pop-up dialog box, choose Owner. In Outlook, choose Contact. The owner's name is listed under Owner.
The owner of the group may have intentionally chosen to restrict who can send messages to it, and they may not want to adjust the existing restriction. In this case, you'll have to contact the group members by some other means, such as sending an email message to their individual email addresses or contacting them by phone.
Was this helpful? Send feedback to Microsoft<http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=525931>. _____
More Info for Email Admins Status code: 550 5.7.124
This error occurs when the owner of the distribution group or security group has set up the group to accept messages only from certain addresses. Even a group owner may not be automatically granted permission to send messages to the group.
To fix this issue, the group owner must add the sender's address to the group's allowed senders list. Usually this issue can only be fixed by the group owner.
For more information and steps to fix this issue, see Fix email delivery issues for error code 5.7.124 in Office 365<http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=532892>.

Dear Helpdesk Staff,
 
Could you please change the permission of the group EEX-Students@msoe.edu such that I can deliver email to this group.  Thank you.
 
Rich Kelnhofer
 
 
Richard W. Kelnhofer, Ph.D.
Program Director – Electrical Engineering
Milwaukee School of Engineering
414-277-2306
 
 
 
 
_____________________________________________
From: Microsoft Outlook
Sent: Wednesday, February 10, 2016 12:56 PM
To: Kelnhofer, Dr. Richard
Subject: Undeliverable: CS 498-001
 
 
http://products.office.com/en-us/CMSImages/Office365Logo_Orange.png?version=b8d100a9-0a8b-8e6a-88e1-ef488fee0470       
Your message to the group EEX-Students@msoe.edu couldn't be delivered.
       
The group EEX-Students only accepts messages from people on its allowed senders list, and your email address isn't on the list.
       
kelnhofer        Office 365       EEX-Students    
Sender           Action Required 
                                       
                Sender not allowed      

How to Fix It   
Ask the owner of the group to grant you permission to send to the group, and then try to send a message again. If the group belongs to a different organization than yours, contact the organization's customer service department for assistance. If the group is in your organization and you don't know who the group owner is, you can find it by doing the following in either Outlook on the web or Outlook:      
 
  • Open your Sent folder, and then select the original message.
  • If you're using Outlook on the web, select the group name located on the To or CC line. If you're using Outlook, double-click the group name on the To or CC line.
  • In Outlook on the web, from the pop-up dialog box, choose Owner. In Outlook, choose Contact. The owner's name is listed under Owner.
    •
 
The owner of the group may have intentionally chosen to restrict who can send messages to it, and they may not want to adjust the existing restriction. In this case, you'll have to contact the group members by some other means, such as sending an email message to their individual email addresses or contacting them by phone.   

Was this helpful? Send feedback to Microsoft.   
  _____  

More Info for Email Admins      
Status code: 550 5.7.124

This error occurs when the owner of the distribution group or security group has set up the group to accept messages only from certain addresses. Even a group owner may not be automatically granted permission to send messages to the group.

To fix this issue, the group owner must add the sender's address to the group's allowed senders list. Usually this issue can only be fixed by the group owner.

For more information and steps to fix this issue, see Fix email delivery issues for error code 5.7.124 in Office 365.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi trevisj,
Another way to reset your outlook profile is to delete and re-add the profile to your computer.
Here are some steps you can take to do this.
1. Close Outlook and navigate to Control Panel 2. Go to the view by drop-down and pick Small Icons. 3. Click on the Icon that says "Mail (32-bit)" 4. Click on the bottom button that says "Show Profiles" 5. Click on each profile and click "Remove". 6. Click "Apply" and then "OK" 7. Restart your computer and open Outlook. It will prompt you for a new profile name and for you to enter in your username and password for your e-mail account.
Please let us know if you have any issues after following these steps.
Thanks, MSOE Information Technology Tier 1 Helpdesk Team Benjamin Mahon 414-277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi trevisj,

Another way to reset your outlook profile is to delete and re-add the profile to your computer.

Here are some steps you can take to do this.

1. Close Outlook and navigate to Control Panel
2. Go to the view by drop-down and pick Small Icons.
3. Click on the Icon that says "Mail (32-bit)"
4. Click on the bottom button that says "Show Profiles"
5. Click on each profile and click "Remove".
6. Click "Apply" and then "OK"
7. Restart your computer and open Outlook. It will prompt you for a new profile name and for you to enter in your username and password for your e-mail account.

Please let us know if you have any issues after following these steps.


Thanks,

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Computer not charging
helpdesk-ticket.description: My laptop doesn't appear to be charging.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: My laptop doesn't appear to be charging.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi schwanebeck, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5551
I have two possibilites you could try.
1) Perform a hard reset. In order to this, pull the battery and the charger and hold the power button for 15-30 seconds.
2) Try another charger. If possible, borrow someone's charger and see if it begins to charge. If it does, you can come in to the helpdesk and we will replace your charger.
Please let me know if this resolves your issue,
Alexander Schroeder
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi schwanebeck,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5551

I have two possibilites you could try.

1) Perform a hard reset.
     In order to this, pull the battery and the charger and hold the power button for 15-30 seconds.

2) Try another charger.
     If possible, borrow someone's charger and see if it begins to charge.  If it does, you can come in to the helpdesk and we will replace your charger.

Please let me know if this resolves your issue,

Alexander Schroeder

helpdesk-note.body:
I played around with the cords and now it is charging. The weird thing is it was plugged in and attached to my computer but not charging. But, as soon as I pulled out the cord everything died. So, the juice was running into my computer, but the battery was not being charged. I am now fully charged.
Thanks
Tom

Tom

Rob

The projector in room 62 is not displaying red. We’ve tried using a different VGA cable, but that did not help.
 
Rob

helpdesk-note.body: sending to a/v team

helpdesk-note.body: Room is open from 1-2PM and after 4PM (2/16).
helpdesk-note.body-html: Room is open from 1-2PM and after 4PM (2/16).

helpdesk-note.body: I tried using a new VGA cable and the picture still had no red. I replaced the lamp and filter and the result was the same. I couldn't find any issues with the color settings on the projector, so it's most likely an issue with the vga cable that connects to the projector or another one of those cables in the process.
helpdesk-note.body-html: I tried using a new VGA cable and the picture still had no red. I replaced the lamp and filter and the result was the same. I couldn't find any issues with the color settings on the projector, so it's most likely an issue with the vga cable that connects to the projector or another one of those cables in the process.

helpdesk-note.body: I can verify that the red not showing up is a VGA specific issue. I plugged in the hdmi and red was showing up just fine.
helpdesk-note.body-html: I can verify that the red not showing up is a VGA specific issue. I plugged in the hdmi and red was showing up just fine.

helpdesk-note.body: We've replaced both the projector and the wall connection. I've responded to Rob Hasker in a separate email message.
helpdesk-note.body-html: We've replaced both the projector and the wall connection. I've responded to Rob Hasker in a separate email message.

Hi hoadley, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5591

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Lawrence Skuse,
To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus.
First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time. Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once!
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu
For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following. 1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”. 2. Open Credential Manager. 3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials” 4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…” 5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt. 6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook. 7. Outlook will ask you for your new password. 8. Outlook will start updating.
The password to log in to your laptop may remain the same as it was before you changed it. We can see, you recently changed your password at 2/16/2016 1:29 AM (CST) Please feel free to reply to this email if you have any concerns or questions.
Thanks Rishabh Gupta Help Desk Technician 414-277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Lawrence Skuse,

To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus.

First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu
This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time.
Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once! 
 
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu

For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following.
1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”.
2. Open Credential Manager.
3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials”
4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…”
5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt.
6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook.
7. Outlook will ask you for your new password.
8. Outlook will start updating.

The password to log in to your laptop may remain the same as it was before you changed it. We can see, you recently changed your password at 2/16/2016 1:29 AM (CST)
Please feel free to reply to this email if you have any concerns or questions.

Thanks
Rishabh Gupta
Help Desk Technician

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Password Reset Request
helpdesk-ticket.description: Password was reset. Send steps to change.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: Password was reset. Send steps to change.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi sekhona,
To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus. First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time. Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once!
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu Your computer will recognize this new password For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following. 1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”. 2. Open Credential Manager. 3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials” 4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…” 5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt. 6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook. 7. Outlook will ask you for your new password. 8. Outlook will start updating. Thanks
Your Default Password is “Msoe######MMDDYY”. Where ###### is your 6 digit ID number and MMDDYY is your Birthday with 2 digits for each (last 2 digits for year)
I will mark this resolved.
Thanks Rishabh Gupta Help Desk Technician
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi sekhona,

To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus.
First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu
This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time.
Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once! 
 
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu
Your computer will recognize this new password 
For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following.
1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”.
2. Open Credential Manager.
3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials”
4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…”
5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt.
6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook.
7. Outlook will ask you for your new password.
8. Outlook will start updating.
Thanks
 
Your Default Password is “Msoe######MMDDYY”.
 Where ###### is your 6 digit ID number and MMDDYY is your Birthday with 2 digits for each (last 2 digits for year)

I will mark this resolved. 

Thanks
Rishabh Gupta
Help Desk Technician

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Follow You on Personal Laptop
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Walked through how to install Follow You Printing on personal laptop
Instructions 1-Connect to MSOE wireless 2-In the search bar under the Start menu, type \\printers.msoe.edu 3-You will be prompted for a username and password. For the username, enter MSOE\ before entering your MSOE username (Domain: below password space should then change to MSOE) and type in MSOE Password 4-Window should come up with all printers available. Install Follow You Printing.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Walked through how to install Follow You Printing on personal laptop

Instructions
1-Connect to MSOE wireless
2-In the search bar under the Start menu, type \\printers.msoe.edu
3-You will be prompted for a username and password. For the username, enter MSOE\ before entering your MSOE username (Domain: below password space should then change to MSOE) and type in MSOE Password
4-Window should come up with all printers available. Install Follow You Printing.

In Outlook on the web, select this NDR, then select the link "To send this message again, click here." Then delete and retype the entire recipient address. If prompted with an Auto-Complete List suggestion don't select it. After typing the complete address, click Send.
·         Contact the recipient (by phone, for example) to check that the address exists and is correct.
·         The recipient may have set up email forwarding to an incorrect address. Ask them to check that any forwarding they've set up is working correctly.
·         Clear the recipient Auto-Complete List in Outlook or Outlook on the web by following the steps in this article: Fix email delivery issues for error code 5.1.1 in Office 365, and then send the message again. Retype the entire recipient address before selecting Send.

More Info for Email Admins
Status code: 550 5.1.1

This error occurs because the sender sent a message to an email address outside of Office 365, but the address is incorrect or doesn't exist at the destination domain. The error is reported by the recipient domain's email server, but most often it must be fixed by the person who sent the message. If the steps in the How to Fix It section above don't fix the problem, and you're the email admin for the recipient, try one or more of the following:

The email address exists and is correct - Confirm that the recipient address exists, is correct, and is accepting messages.

Synchronize your directories - If you have a hybrid environment and are using directory synchronization make sure the recipient's email address is synced correctly in both Office 365 and in your on-premises directory.

Errant forwarding rule - Check for forwarding rules that aren't behaving as expected. Forwarding can be set up by an admin via mail flow rules or mailbox forwarding address settings, or by the recipient via the Inbox Rules feature.

Mail flow settings and MX records are correct - Misconfigured mail flow or MX record settings can cause this error. Check your Office 365 mail flow settings to make sure your domain and any mail flow connectors are set up correctly. Also, work with your domain registrar to make sure the MX records for your domain are configured correctly.
